<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level CREATE ACL
    that grants the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_agent` UNCONDITIONAL create
    access on the `x_[scope]_case_party` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_[scope]`. This is the CREATE companion to the sibling
    READ ACL at ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml and
    the WRITE ACL at ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml;
    together with the case_manager-specific ACL at
    ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_create_manager.xml, the case_party-table
    create-permission set is fully and exhaustively realized for the
    three scoped roles (manager: yes; agent: yes; viewer: deny-by-default).

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row, mirrored at the
        case_party table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at party level; case_agent can write only
         parties where parent case is 'Assigned only'"):
            | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
            | x_[scope]_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Create = Yes" cell of that row for
        the case_party table. The "Yes Assigned only" Read cell is
        authored by ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml;
        the "Yes Assigned only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No"
        Delete cell is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_[scope]_case_party_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-
        level ACLs are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for
        an operation cannot perform that operation). Each row of the ACL
        matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files; this per-cell
        granularity is what lets the Update Set add or remove role
        privileges independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles create coverage on
        case_party:
          - case_manager: Create=Yes  -> ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_create_manager.xml
          - case_agent:   Create=Yes  -> THIS FILE
          - case_viewer:  Create=No   -> deliberate absence of any ACL
        Together these three facts implement the AAP's case_party
        creation contract: both managers and agents can author party
        association records (linking persons or organizations to cases),
        but the lowest-privilege viewer (audit / compliance / supervisor
        tier) cannot.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
           case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
           full access."
        The clause "case_agent cannot access UNASSIGNED cases" applies
        to read and write only - it is logically inapplicable to create
        because a record cannot be "assigned" to anyone before it
        exists. Therefore this ACL grants create unconditionally to any
        caller holding the x_[scope]_case_agent role; downstream
        visibility of and edits to the created case_party record are
        governed by the read/write _agent_assigned siblings, which DO
        restrict access to rows whose parent case is "Assigned only" to
        the calling user (i.e., where parent case `assigned_agent` =
        current user OR parent case `assigned_group` contains current
        user, per AAP Section 0.5.6).
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig map." This ACL is the
        table-level CREATE binding for the mid-tier scoped role on the
        party-association domain.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): The ServiceNow target replaces
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.getRolesToPrivileges() (a
        Map<String, List<Object>> bound from
        application.rolesToPrivileges configuration) and
        AcmPluginUrlPrivilege URL-method enforcement with declarative
        scoped record-level ACLs. This XML record is therefore the
        declarative equivalent of the conceptual (case_agent, CREATE on
        PARTY) cell of that ArkCase map.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Polymorphic association via single-table choice
        + UI Policy): the case_party table is the single-table collapse
        of ArkCase's two separate association tables (acm_person_assoc
        and acm_person_org_assoc, originally backed by
        PersonAssociation.java and PersonOrganizationAssociation.java).
        Because both Person and Organization parties live in one table
        differentiated by the `party_type` choice field, ONE create ACL
        suffices for both kinds of party - there is no separate
        person-create vs organization-create ACL to author. The UI
        Policy at ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
        handles which reference field (`person` -> sys_user vs
        `organization` -> core_company) is required at submit time.
      - Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules) - "People and
        Organizations associated to cases as typed parties." This
        success-criterion bullet implies that authenticated case_agent
        users must be able to create party records (both Person and
        Organization variants) on cases assigned to them via the
        internal native form view (the primary party-authoring surface
        for agents). THIS ACL is what makes that path permitted.
      - Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping Verbatim) - case_party schema:
            | Field        | Type                            | Constraints                  |
            | case         | Reference -> x_[scope]_case     | Mandatory                    |
            | party_type   | Choice                          | Person, Organization         |
            | person       | Reference -> sys_user           | Conditional (party_type=Person)       |
            | organization | Reference -> core_company       | Conditional (party_type=Organization) |
            | role_label   | String(100)                     | Mandatory                    |
        Note that case_party does NOT carry its own assigned_group /
        assigned_agent fields - the "Assigned only" predicate from the
        AAP's matrix is therefore evaluated against the PARENT CASE row
        (referenced via current.case) by the read/write _agent_assigned
        siblings. For CREATE this dereference is irrelevant because no
        current row exists pre-insert; this is the second reason CREATE
        is unconditional (in addition to "current is null pre-insert").

    Why <advanced>false</advanced> (in contrast to read/write _agent_assigned):
      The READ and WRITE agent-assigned siblings on case_party use
      <advanced>true</advanced> so the platform invokes their CDATA
      scripted condition that dereferences current.case via
      getRefRecord() and evaluates "parentCase.assigned_agent ==
      gs.getUserID() OR parentCase.assigned_group contains current
      user." That predicate cannot be evaluated at create time because:
        1. No `current` record exists yet - the row is being inserted at
           the moment the ACL fires. The platform binds `current` to a
           freshly-instantiated record skeleton with the caller's POSTed
           field values; calling getRefRecord() against a not-yet-saved
           reference field on that skeleton returns an unstable / empty
           result that produces false positives or false negatives.
        2. Even if `current.case` were already populated (e.g., the
           form pre-fills it from the parent case context the user
           navigated from via the case form's related-list "New" UI
           action), checking parent-case assignment at create-time
           would merely duplicate the parent-case READ ACL the platform
           has ALREADY enforced (the user could not have opened the
           parent case to start a related-list create unless the case-
           level agent_assigned read ACL had already permitted it). Re-
           running the same predicate at party-create time is redundant.
        3. Per the AAP design pattern in Section 0.4.3 the "Assigned
           only" predicate is reserved for read/write ACLs; create is
           a binary role check.
      Consequences of <advanced>false</advanced>:
        - <condition/>  is evaluated as an empty encoded query (no row
                        filter; permits the request).
        - <script/>     is NOT evaluated (the platform skips it when
                        advanced=false).
        - <roles>       remains the sole admission gate: callers
                        holding x_[scope]_case_agent are granted create;
                        callers without the role are denied.
      This is the standard ServiceNow pattern for "any role member can
      perform this operation, no per-row predicate" and matches the
      agent prompt's "create has no condition" rule verbatim.

    Why creation is unconditional and what governs the created row afterward:
      Pre-creation there is no record to evaluate against - any "row-
      level" check on parent-case assignment is logically impossible at
      this stage of the request lifecycle. Once the case_party record
      is inserted, downstream access is governed by:
        (a) The read/write _agent_assigned party-level ACLs (siblings
            of this file), which restrict the creating agent's
            subsequent visibility of and edits to the freshly-created
            party to the rows where the PARENT CASE has the agent as
            assigned_agent or as a member of assigned_group. This
            means an agent CAN insert a party pointing at any case
            row, but if they pick a case to which they have no
            assignment, the very next read of that party (e.g., upon
            redirect to the party form after submit) will be denied by
            the party-level read ACL - producing a "you-just-created-
            it-but-cannot-see-it" outcome that is harmless and self-
            correcting.
        (b) The case-table read/write _agent_assigned ACLs (siblings
            of this file at one level higher, governing the
            x_[scope]_case table itself), which already restrict which
            cases an agent can OPEN to begin a related-list create
            from. In normal operational flow the agent only ever sees
            a "Create related party" UI action on cases they already
            have access to; the case-table ACLs therefore implicitly
            funnel all new party creates onto cases the agent is
            allowed to act on.
        (c) Mandatory-field constraints declared on the dictionary
            entries (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml): per AAP
            Section 0.5.7 every party field except the conditional
            person/organization references is mandatory at all times
            (case, party_type, role_label), and the conditional fields
            are mandatory based on the chosen party_type per the UI
            Policy at ../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml.
            Even if the agent attempts to insert a degenerate party
            row to probe the ACL, the platform rejects the row at the
            schema layer before the ACL evaluator returns success.
        (d) The conditional UI Policy enforcement of person /
            organization required-field state ensures that any
            inserted party row is internally consistent (Person rows
            carry a person reference, Organization rows carry an
            organization reference), so the agent cannot create
            malformed polymorphic rows.
      In short: an agent CAN create a party but cannot weaponize the
      privilege to inject parties onto unassigned cases, because the
      platform's standard navigation surface only exposes the create
      action from cases the agent already has access to, and any out-
      of-band attempt to insert a party on an unassigned case results
      in an immediately-invisible row with no operational utility.

    Why a separate file per role (instead of one create ACL with both roles):
      ServiceNow allows multiple roles in a single <roles> field as a
      comma-separated list, and that pattern technically also satisfies
      the AAP. However, the established convention in this Update Set
      (and in industry practice for scoped applications) is one ACL
      record per (table, operation, role) triple. Reasons:
        - Single-responsibility: each ACL record encodes exactly one
          authorization fact; if the AAP later removes case_agent's
          create privilege on case_party (e.g., to enforce a stricter
          intake-via-portal-only policy where only managers can author
          party associations), the change is a single-file deletion
          with no risk of accidentally also revoking case_manager's
          create privilege.
        - Auditability: the file inventory under ../acl/ becomes a
          self-documenting matrix - the presence or absence of a file
          named x_[scope]_<table>_<operation>_<role>.xml is the answer
          to "does role X have privilege Y on table Z?".
        - Update Set diff clarity: when the Update Set is re-imported
          on a fresh PDI, each ACL is a discrete row in the preview
          screen, making it easy to spot that case_agent's create
          privilege was installed (alongside case_manager's) versus a
          single combined row that would obscure the role membership.
      The companion ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_create_manager.xml file
      authors the case_manager half of the Create=Yes pair using the
      same per-role-per-operation pattern.

    Mirror relationship to ../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_agent.xml and
    ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_agent.xml:
      This file is the case_party-table analog of the agent-create ACLs
      already authored for the case table at
      ../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_agent.xml and for the case_task table
      at ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_agent.xml. The ONLY
      differences between those files and this one are:
        - <name>           x_[scope]_case_party  (vs x_[scope]_case
                                                  vs x_[scope]_case_task)
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_[scope]_case_party.create.case_agent")
                                                  (= a4889da05a5e043e0f7af2c521984a55)
                           (vs MD5("x_[scope]_case.create.case_agent")
                            = 8ae51c961898321cb00dc4018d7e88d5
                            vs MD5("x_[scope]_case_task.create.case_agent")
                            = e0d5a22fa8de097d5b478125eb6dfc67)
        - <sys_name>       x_[scope]_case_party  (vs the corresponding
                                                  table names)
        - <sys_update_name> sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_party_create_agent
                                                  (vs the corresponding update names)
        - <description>    references the case_party table semantic
      All other fields (active, admin_overrides, advanced, condition,
      operation, roles, script, sys_class_name, sys_created_by,
      sys_policy, sys_scope, sys_package, type, audit timestamps) are
      byte-for-byte identical so that the agent's create privilege is
      uniformly unconditional across all three scoped tables (case,
      case_task, case_party) in the scoped application as the AAP
      matrix mandates.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single
        configuration map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`)
        keyed by the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that
        model, an "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated
        with privilege identifiers such as
        `acm-person-association-create` or
        `acm-organization-association-create`, and those privilege
        strings would have been resolved at runtime against URL-method
        bindings declared in
        ApplicationPluginPrivilegesConfig.getApplicationPluginsPrivileges()
        via AcmPluginUrlPrivilege. The ServiceNow target replaces this
        bifurcated model (declarative privilege list + imperative URL-
        binding) with a single declarative scoped record-level ACL:
        this XML record IS the (case_agent, CREATE on PARTY) cell of
        that conceptual map. Because the ServiceNow case_party table
        collapses ArkCase's two separate Java association entities into
        one, this single ACL replaces what would have been two ArkCase
        privilege bindings (one for person-create, one for
        organization-create).
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in
        ArkCase (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus the role-name normalization step that uppercased the
        role, replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods
        with double-underscores, and prepended the `ROLE_` prefix from
        RolePrivilegesConstants). All of this Java service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator and by static role names declared
        in scope-prefixed sys_user_role records (the case_agent role
        is declared in
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml; this ACL
        references it by literal name in the <roles> field). The
        role-name-normalization step in particular is replaced by the
        scoped-application convention of using literal scope-prefixed
        role names (e.g., x_[scope]_case_agent) directly in the
        <roles> field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no case
        folding occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque
        identifier resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role
        table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves
        into the x_[scope] scope (sys_scope = x_[scope], sys_package =
        x_[scope]). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_[scope]_case_party (NOT any OOB
        ServiceNow table such as `task` or `core_company`), and
        <roles> references the scoped role x_[scope]_case_agent. Per
        AAP Section 0.3.2 "Global scope changes of any kind" are
        explicitly prohibited.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>,
        <roles>, <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their
        targets by name / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply
        time. The <sys_id> below is THIS record's own deterministic
        primary key (MD5 of the canonical identifier
        "x_[scope]_case_party.create.case_agent", a stable key for
        this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the
        ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-
        trip Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_[scope]_case_party`
        with NO dot. ServiceNow's create operation has no concept of
        "create this specific column" - field-level ACLs apply only to
        read/write/none. The <type>record</type> field below confirms
        this is a row-level (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-
        flavored ACL.
      - Operation = create: corresponds exactly to the "Create = Yes"
        cell in the AAP matrix for the case_agent role on the
        case_party table.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that
        allows the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is
        required so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair,
        or seed scoped data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the
        seed_demo_data.js script seeds parties under the platform's
        elevated context). It does NOT widen case_agent privileges -
        case_agents without admin still see exactly what this ACL
        permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set
        commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above.
        The platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is
        empty; no row-level filter applies (and none is meaningful
        pre-insert).
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform
        skips it because advanced=false.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app
          record - ensures sys_package source="x_[scope]" resolves)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - ensures
          sys_scope display_value="Case Management" resolves)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml (resolves
          <name>x_[scope]_case_party</name>)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's create access during round-trip
          verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml (demo
          parties inserted by the seed pass need this ACL in place if
          any seed runs under the demo agent's identity context; the
          seed_demo_data.js script itself runs as admin so
          admin_overrides bypasses this ACL during seeding, but post-
          seed agent-side smoke tests against the demo dataset depend
          on this ACL being applied)

    The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim per AAP
    convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); the
    Personal Developer Instance auto-assigns the actual concrete scope
    id at App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-
    time renaming propagates consistently across all bracketed
    placeholders in this artifact. The deterministic sys_id below is
    computed against the `[scope]` literal and remains stable across
    re-imports onto fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_[scope]_case_agent role to create case_party records.</description>
        <name>x_[scope]_case_party</name>
        <operation>create</operation>
        <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>a4889da05a5e043e0f7af2c521984a55</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_[scope]_case_party</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_party_create_agent</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
